{
 "response": "# Perspective Audit \u2014 Multi-Step Checkout Form With Broken Error Association\n\n**Component/artifact reviewed:** `CheckoutForm` (React multi-step checkout \u2014 Shipping \u2192 Payment \u2192 Review)\n**Perspectives escalated for deep review:** Environmental Contrast (MEDIUM), Keyboard & Motor (MEDIUM), Screen Reader & Semantic Structure (HIGH), Cognitive & Neurodivergent (MEDIUM)\n**Perspectives at LOW (not reviewed):** Magnification & Reflow, Vestibular & Motion Sensitivity, Auditory Access\n\nEvidence citations use the component source as provided (JSX line references approximate to the fixture; CSS cited by selector + declared value). Contrast ratios computed from the declared hex values against the resolved background (page/wrapper background resolves to white \u2014 no background is set on `.checkout-wrapper`).\n\n---\n\n## Perspective 2 \u2014 Environmental Contrast (MEDIUM)\n\n**WCAG criteria (AA):** 1.3.3, 1.4.1, 1.4.3, 1.4.11\n\n### JTBD checklist\n\n- **Normal text contrast \u2265 4.5:1 (1.4.3)** \u2014 PASS. Step labels: `#fff` on `#2e7d32` \u2248 5.1:1, `#fff` on `#1565c0` \u2248 5.75:1, `#555` on `#e0e0e0` \u2248 5.6:1. Inline/summary error text `#b71c1c` on white \u2248 6.6:1 and on `#fff3f3` \u2248 6.1:1. Field labels/legends inherit default near-black on white (~21:1). All measured text passes.\n- **Large text \u2265 3:1 (1.4.3)** \u2014 N/A. No text meets the large-text threshold (all \u226416px; step labels are 14px/600 which is *normal* text, not large \u2014 and it still passes 4.5:1).\n- **UI component boundaries/states \u2265 3:1 (1.4.11)** \u2014 FINDING. Default input border `2px solid #ccc` on white \u2248 **1.6:1**. See Finding EC-2.\n- **Color never the sole indicator (1.4.1)** \u2014 FINDING. Step indicator communicates complete/active/upcoming purely by background color. See Finding EC-1.\n- **Instructions don't rely on sensory characteristics (1.3.3)** \u2014 PASS. Error summary and button labels use explicit text (\"Please fix the following errors\", \"Next: Payment\"); no \"click the green/right\" style instructions.\n- **Functional in forced-colors / Windows High Contrast** \u2014 FINDING (same root as EC-1). In forced-colors mode all three step-state backgrounds collapse to a single system color, erasing complete/active/upcoming distinction; there is no border, text, or icon fallback. Folded into Finding EC-1. (The invalid-state red border also flattens, but the inline error *text* survives, so error state remains perceivable.)\n\n### Findings\n\n**Finding EC-1:** Step-progress state (complete / active / upcoming) is conveyed by background color alone. The three states differ only in `.step-indicator li` background (`#2e7d32` / `#1565c0` / `#e0e0e0`); the visible label text (\"Shipping\", \"Payment\", \"Review\") is identical across states, and there is no checkmark, \"current\"/\"done\" text, shape, or pattern. A user with color vision deficiency, a grayscale display, or forced-colors mode cannot tell which steps are done or which is current.\n**WCAG:** 1.4.1 Use of Color\n**Perspective:** Environmental Contrast\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Visual Design (secondary: Front-End Dev)\n**Evidence:** JSX `<li className={idx < currentStep ? 'complete' : idx === currentStep ? 'active' : 'upcoming'}>`; CSS `.step-indicator li.complete/.active/.upcoming` set only `background`/`color`. No non-color differentiator in markup or CSS.\n**Fix:** Add a non-color indicator per state \u2014 e.g., a \"\u2713 Completed\" / \"Current step\" text label or icon appended to each `<li>`, and pair with `aria-current=\"step\"` (see SR-4). Ensure the differentiator survives forced-colors (use `border` or text, not background alone).\n\n**Finding EC-2:** Text-input borders are below the non-text contrast threshold in their default (resting) state. The declared border `2px solid #ccc` against the white page background is \u2248 1.6:1, under the 3:1 minimum for identifying a UI component boundary. In bright-light / low-contrast-display conditions (the core environmental-contrast scenario) the field boundaries are effectively invisible; users locate fields only by the adjacent label. (Note: the *invalid* border `#b71c1c` \u2248 6.6:1 and the focus outline `#1565c0` \u2248 5.75:1 both pass \u2014 the failure is specifically the default state.)\n**WCAG:** 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast\n**Perspective:** Environmental Contrast\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Visual Design (secondary: Front-End Dev)\n**Evidence:** CSS `.form-group input { border: 2px solid #ccc; }` on a container with no background (resolves to white). Computed ratio \u2248 1.6:1.\n**Fix:** Darken the default border to \u2265 3:1 against white (e.g., `#767676` \u2248 4.5:1 or at minimum `#949494` \u2248 3:1), or add a distinguishing fill so the field is identifiable without relying on the border.\n\n---\n\n## Perspective 5 \u2014 Keyboard & Motor Access (MEDIUM)\n\n**WCAG criteria (AA):** 1.3.4, 2.1.1, 2.1.2, 2.4.1, 2.4.3, 2.4.7, 2.4.13, 2.5.1, 2.5.2, 2.5.3, 2.5.7, 2.5.8\n\n### JTBD checklist\n\n- **All interactive elements keyboard-operable (2.1.1)** \u2014 PASS. Every control is a native `<input>` or `<button>`; no `div`/`span` click handlers. Inputs, \"Next\" (`type=\"button\"` + `onClick`), and \"Place Order\" (`type=\"submit\"`) are all reachable and operable.\n- **No keyboard trap (2.1.2)** \u2014 PASS. No custom focus capture, modal, or `tabindex` manipulation.\n- **Skip link targets main (2.4.1)** \u2014 N/A. Component excerpt with no repeated navigation blocks to bypass.\n- **Focus order logical (2.4.3)** \u2014 PASS. DOM order = visual order: error summary (no focusables inside), then fields top-to-bottom, then action button.\n- **Focus indicator \u22652px, \u22653:1 (2.4.7, 2.4.13)** \u2014 PASS. Inputs: `outline: 3px solid #1565c0; outline-offset: 2px` \u2248 5.75:1 on white. Buttons: same outline; although the outline color equals the button background, `outline-offset: 2px` renders the ring on the white page with a 2px gap, so it remains \u2248 5.75:1 and visible. Meets thickness and contrast bars.\n- **Multi-point gestures have single-pointer alternative (2.5.1)** \u2014 N/A. No multi-point/path gestures.\n- **Activation on up-event (2.5.2)** \u2014 PASS. Native buttons activate on `click` (up-event); user can abort by dragging off.\n- **Visible label matches accessible name (2.5.3)** \u2014 FINDING. `firstName` and `address` have no accessible name at all (broken label association), so voice-control users cannot target them by the visible label. See Finding KM-1.\n- **Every drag operation has click alternative (2.5.7)** \u2014 N/A. No drag interactions.\n- **Targets \u2265 24\u00d724 CSS px (2.5.8)** \u2014 PASS. Inputs \u2248 40px tall (10px padding + 16px text + 2px borders), full-width. Buttons \u2248 40px tall (12px vertical padding + 16px text) with 24px horizontal padding. Both exceed 24px.\n- **Portrait and landscape (1.3.4)** \u2014 PASS. No orientation lock; `max-width: 560px` layout reflows in both orientations.\n\n### Findings\n\n**Finding KM-1:** The `firstName` and `address` inputs expose no accessible name (their `<label>` elements point at non-existent ids \u2014 `htmlFor=\"first-name\"` vs `id=\"firstName\"`, and `htmlFor=\"street-address\"` vs `id=\"address\"` \u2014 and there is no `aria-label`). A speech-recognition user who says \"click First Name\" / \"click Street Address\" has no matching accessible name to target, so voice control cannot reach these fields by their visible label. (Keyboard Tab still reaches them, so a fallback path exists \u2014 hence MAJOR, not CRITICAL. The same defect is CRITICAL from the screen-reader perspective, where there is no fallback \u2014 see Finding SR-1.)\n**WCAG:** 2.5.3 Label in Name\n**Perspective:** Keyboard & Motor\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** JSX `<label htmlFor=\"first-name\">First Name</label>` + `<input id=\"firstName\" \u2026>`; `<label htmlFor=\"street-address\">Street Address</label>` + `<input id=\"address\" \u2026>`. Accessible name computes to empty for both.\n**Fix:** Correct each `htmlFor` to match the input `id` (`first-name`\u2192`firstName`, `street-address`\u2192`address`). This restores the accessible name so it contains the visible label text.\n\n---\n\n## Perspective 6 \u2014 Screen Reader & Semantic Structure (HIGH)\n\n**WCAG criteria (AA):** 1.1.1, 1.3.1, 1.3.2, 2.4.2, 2.4.4, 2.4.6, 3.1.1, 3.1.2, 3.3.1, 3.3.2, 4.1.2, 4.1.3\n\n### JTBD checklist\n\n- **Landmark regions present (1.3.1)** \u2014 FINDING (context-dependent). The component root is a plain `<div className=\"checkout-wrapper\">`; no `<main>`. If this form is the page's primary content it must sit within a `<main>` landmark. See Finding SR-6 (verification-gated).\n- **Heading hierarchy, `<h1>` present (2.4.6)** \u2014 FINDING (context-dependent). The component uses `<h2>` for the error summary and the Review section but contains no `<h1>`. Whether the page supplies an `<h1>` cannot be confirmed from source. See Finding SR-6.\n- **Informative images have alt; decorative alt=\"\" (1.1.1)** \u2014 N/A. No images.\n- **DOM order matches visual reading order (1.3.2)** \u2014 PASS.\n- **Unique descriptive `<title>` (2.4.2)** \u2014 Cannot confirm from source; the SPA never updates a title per step (related to SR-5). Verification-gated.\n- **Link text describes destination (2.4.4)** \u2014 FINDING. The error summary lists errors as plain `<li>` text rather than links to the fields, so there is no in-context navigation to the erroneous inputs. See Finding SR-3.\n- **`lang` on `<html>` (3.1.1)** \u2014 FINDING (context-dependent). Not present in component scope; verify at page level. See Finding SR-6.\n- **Foreign-language phrases wrapped in `lang` (3.1.2)** \u2014 N/A. All content English.\n- **Every input has visible label + programmatic association (3.3.2)** \u2014 FINDING (CRITICAL). `firstName` and `address` labels are not associated (id mismatch); those inputs have no accessible name. `lastName`, `city`, `cardNumber`, `cardExpiry` are correctly associated (PASS). See Finding SR-1.\n- **Errors identify the field and are associated via `aria-describedby` (3.3.1)** \u2014 FINDING. No input has `aria-describedby`, and the inline `.error-text` spans have no `id`, so field-level error text is orphaned from its field. See Finding SR-2.\n- **Custom widgets use correct ARIA roles/state (4.1.2)** \u2014 FINDING. The step indicator `<ol>` exposes no current/completed state to assistive tech (no `aria-current`, no textual state). See Finding SR-4.\n- **Status messages use `aria-live` (4.1.3)** \u2014 FINDING. The error summary is inserted with no `role=\"alert\"`/`aria-live` and no focus move, so validation failures are silent to screen readers. See Finding SR-2. Step advances are likewise unannounced. See Finding SR-5.\n- **SPA step changes: title updates, focus managed, change announced (4.1.3)** \u2014 FINDING. Advancing a step swaps the fieldset with no announcement and no title update. See Finding SR-5.\n\n### Findings\n\n**Finding SR-1:** Two required inputs expose no accessible name. `<label htmlFor=\"first-name\">` does not match `<input id=\"firstName\">`, and `<label htmlFor=\"street-address\">` does not match `<input id=\"address\">`; neither input has `aria-label`/`aria-labelledby`. A screen reader announces each as an unnamed \"edit text, required, invalid\" \u2014 the user cannot tell which field they are in. This fires the perspective red flag (\"form inputs without any label\"). Because the label is *visually* present but programmatically detached, there is no fallback for a screen-reader user.\n**WCAG:** 3.3.2 Labels or Instructions; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value (also 1.3.1 Info and Relationships)\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** CRITICAL (red flag \u2014 inputs without a programmatic label)\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: Content Author)\n**Evidence:** `<label htmlFor=\"first-name\">First Name</label>` + `<input id=\"firstName\" name=\"firstName\" \u2026>`; `<label htmlFor=\"street-address\">Street Address</label>` + `<input id=\"address\" name=\"address\" \u2026>`.\n**Fix:** Align each `htmlFor` with its input `id` (`first-name`\u2192`firstName`, `street-address`\u2192`address`). Verify with the accessibility tree that every field reports its visible label as its name.\n\n**Finding SR-2:** Field-level errors are not programmatically associated, and the error summary is not announced. (a) Each `.error-text` span lacks an `id` and no input carries `aria-describedby`, so a screen-reader user focused on an invalid field hears \"invalid\" / \"required\" (from `aria-invalid` / `aria-required`) but never the corrective message \"First name is required\". (b) The `.error-summary` container has no `role=\"alert\"` / `aria-live` and focus is not moved to it on validation failure, so when \"Next\"/\"Place Order\" fails, a screen-reader user receives no feedback that anything went wrong \u2014 the button label is unchanged and nothing is spoken. This is the highest-impact barrier in the component: a blind user filling an empty required field is left with no indication of why they cannot advance.\n**WCAG:** 3.3.1 Error Identification; 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value; 4.1.3 Status Messages\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** `<span className=\"error-text\">{errors.firstName}</span>` (no `id`); every `<input>` omits `aria-describedby`; `<div className=\"error-summary\">` has no `role`/`aria-live`; `handleNext`/`handleSubmit` set errors but never move focus.\n**Fix:** Give each error span a stable `id` (e.g., `firstName-error`) and add `aria-describedby=\"firstName-error\"` on the matching input (conditionally, only when the error exists). Give the error-summary container `role=\"alert\"` (or `aria-live=\"assertive\"` + `tabindex=\"-1\"`) and move focus to it when validation fails, so the summary is announced.\n\n**Finding SR-3:** The error summary is not navigable to the fields in error. Items render as plain `<li>{message}</li>` rather than as links (`<li><a href=\"#firstName\">\u2026</a></li>`). Even once the summary is announced (SR-2), a screen-reader or keyboard user cannot jump from a listed error to its field and must hunt through the form manually. Errors are still identified in text (so this is a navigation-efficiency degradation with a Tab-through workaround), which is why it is MINOR rather than MAJOR.\n**WCAG:** 3.3.1 Error Identification (technique G139 \u2014 mechanism to navigate to errors)\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MINOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** `<li key={field}>{message}</li>` inside `<ul aria-labelledby=\"error-summary-heading\">`; no anchors, no field ids to target.\n**Fix:** Render each summary item as a link to its field (`<a href=\"#firstName\">First name is required</a>`), which requires the field ids to be stable and focus-styled. Pairs naturally with the SR-1/SR-2 fixes.\n\n**Finding SR-4:** The step indicator exposes no state to assistive technology. The active `<li>` carries no `aria-current=\"step\"`, and completed/upcoming steps carry no textual or ARIA state \u2014 the distinction lives entirely in CSS class + background color. A screen-reader user navigating the `<ol aria-label=\"Checkout steps\">` hears \"Checkout steps, list, 3 items: Shipping, Payment, Review\" with no indication of which step is current or which are done. The fieldset `<legend>` (\"Shipping Information\" / \"Payment Details\") does convey the *current section name* as partial mitigation, but progress and completion state are entirely absent.\n**WCAG:** 4.1.2 Name, Role, Value\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** `<li key={step} className={\u2026'complete'\u2026'active'\u2026'upcoming'}>{step}</li>` \u2014 no `aria-current`, no state text.\n**Fix:** Add `aria-current=\"step\"` to the active `<li>`; expose completion with visually-hidden or visible text (e.g., \"Shipping \u2014 completed\") so state is not color-only (shared fix with EC-1).\n\n**Finding SR-5:** Step transitions are silent and unmanaged. Advancing from Shipping \u2192 Payment unmounts one fieldset and mounts the next with no live announcement and no document-title update; focus is retained on the persistent \"Next\" button (so focus is not lost to `<body>`, a mitigation) but the screen-reader user is never told they are now on \"Step 2 of 3, Payment\". In a multi-step checkout, the loss of \"where am I / what changed\" is a real orientation barrier.\n**WCAG:** 4.1.3 Status Messages (supporting: 2.4.2 Page Titled for per-step context)\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** `handleNext` calls `setCurrentStep(prev => prev + 1)`; conditional `{currentStep === 0 && \u2026}` swaps fieldsets; no announcement, focus move, or title change on transition.\n**Fix:** On step change, move focus to the new step's heading/legend (give it `tabindex=\"-1\"`) or announce \"Step N of 3, <name>\" via a polite live region, and update the document title per step.\n\n**Finding SR-6:** Page-level semantic scaffolding cannot be confirmed from the component and must be verified at integration: (i) no `<main>` landmark wraps the form (1.3.1); (ii) no `<h1>` is present in component scope \u2014 only `<h2>` (2.4.6); (iii) no `lang` attribute on `<html>` is in scope (3.1.1). These are the perspective's landmark/heading/lang red-flag items, but for a component excerpt they may legitimately be supplied by the page shell \u2014 so they are reported as verification items, not auto-CRITICAL red flags.\n**WCAG:** 1.3.1 Info and Relationships; 2.4.6 Headings and Labels; 3.1.1 Language of Page\n**Perspective:** Screen Reader & Semantic Structure\n**Severity:** MINOR `[Human verification required \u2014 cannot be confirmed from source]`\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: Content Author)\n**Evidence:** Component root is `<div className=\"checkout-wrapper\">`; highest heading is `<h2>`; `<html>` not in scope.\n**Fix:** Confirm the form renders inside `<main>`, under a page `<h1>`, on an `<html lang=\"\u2026\">` document. If the component owns the page's primary region, wrap it in `<main>`.\n\n---\n\n## Perspective 7 \u2014 Cognitive & Neurodivergent (MEDIUM)\n\n**WCAG criteria (AA):** 1.3.5, 2.2.1, 2.4.5, 3.2.1, 3.2.2, 3.2.3, 3.2.4, 3.2.6, 3.3.3, 3.3.4, 3.3.7, 3.3.8\n\n### JTBD checklist\n\n- **Error messages suggest specific corrective action (3.3.3)** \u2014 PASS. Validation is presence-only; \"First name is required\" states both the problem and the implied correction. The expiry label carries format guidance \"(MM/YY)\". No cryptic \"invalid input\" messages exist.\n- **Multi-step form does not re-ask earlier info (3.3.7)** \u2014 PASS. `formData` persists across steps; the Review step reads back prior entries; no field is re-collected. Red flag does not fire.\n- **Auth: no transcription/memorization/puzzle; paste & autofill work (3.3.8)** \u2014 PASS. No CAPTCHA or cognitive test; paste is not blocked on any field. (Autofill is impaired by missing `autocomplete` \u2014 see CN-1 \u2014 but that is 1.3.5, not a 3.3.8 puzzle barrier.)\n- **Navigation same relative position across pages (3.2.3)** \u2014 N/A. Single component; no cross-page navigation to compare.\n- **Same-function components consistent (3.2.4)** \u2014 PASS. The forward action is consistently the primary button (\"Next: \u2026\" then \"Place Order\").\n- **Help mechanism consistent location (3.2.6)** \u2014 N/A. No help mechanism present (absence is not a violation).\n- **Focus does not auto-trigger context change (3.2.1)** \u2014 PASS. Focusing a field does nothing beyond focus.\n- **Changing a value does not auto-submit/navigate (3.2.2)** \u2014 PASS. `handleChange` only updates state; advancement requires an explicit button press.\n- **Destructive/committing actions have undo/confirmation/review (3.3.4)** \u2014 PASS. The Review step (step 2) shows Name / Address / Card-ending before \"Place Order\", satisfying the review-and-confirm mechanism for a financial transaction. This is a genuine strength.\n- **More than one way to reach any page (2.4.5)** \u2014 N/A. Single-flow component.\n- **Personal-data inputs have `autocomplete` (1.3.5)** \u2014 FINDING. No input carries an `autocomplete` token. See Finding CN-1.\n- **Timeout warnings give \u2265 20s (2.2.1)** \u2014 N/A. No timeout present.\n- **Avoids unexplained jargon** \u2014 PASS. Plain labels; \"MM/YY\" is conventional and shown.\n- **Neurodivergent \u2014 predictable layout / clear hierarchy / no autoplay or unprompted modal / no reliance on memory** \u2014 PASS. Layout is stable (the only shift is the user-initiated error summary insertion); headings, legends, and spacing give clear hierarchy; the only dialog is the user-triggered `alert('Order placed!')` (prompted, not unprompted); the Review step removes any reliance on recalling earlier entries.\n\n### Findings\n\n**Finding CN-1:** No input declares an `autocomplete` attribute, so browser/assistive autofill cannot populate name, address, or payment fields. For users with cognitive or memory-related disabilities (and motor users, and everyone), autofill removes the burden of recalling and re-typing personal and financial data \u2014 exactly the data this checkout collects. This is a Level AA failure on the fields 1.3.5 targets. A manual-typing workaround exists (hence MAJOR, not CRITICAL).\n**WCAG:** 1.3.5 Identify Input Purpose\n**Perspective:** Cognitive & Neurodivergent\n**Severity:** MAJOR\n**Route to:** Front-End Dev (secondary: UX Design)\n**Evidence:** `<input id=\"firstName\" \u2026>`, `lastName`, `address`, `city`, `cardNumber`, `cardExpiry` \u2014 none declare `autocomplete`.\n**Fix:** Add tokens: `given-name`, `family-name`, `street-address`, `address-level2` (city), `cc-number`, `cc-exp`. This also strengthens the personal-data-purpose signal for AT.\n\n---\n\n## Perspective Audit Summary\n\n**Component/artifact reviewed:** `CheckoutForm` \u2014 multi-step checkout (Shipping \u2192 Payment \u2192 Review)\n**Perspectives escalated for deep review:** Environmental Contrast, Keyboard & Motor, Screen Reader & Semantic Structure, Cognitive & Neurodivergent\n**Perspectives at LOW (not reviewed):** Magnification & Reflow, Vestibular & Motion Sensitivity, Auditory Access\n\n### Findings by Severity\n\n| Severity | Count |\n|---|---|\n| CRITICAL | 1 |\n| MAJOR | 7 |\n| MINOR | 2 |\n| ENHANCEMENT | 0 |\n\n(MINOR count excludes the SR-6 page-scaffolding items, which are verification-gated and listed under Open Questions.)\n\n### Perspectives That Passed\n\nNone of the four escalated perspectives passed cleanly \u2014 each surfaced at least one finding. Notable **strengths** confirmed during the pass (to keep severity honest): native keyboard operability with no traps, adequate focus indicators, \u226524px targets, all *text* contrast passing, four of six labels correctly associated, data preserved across steps (no redundant entry, 3.3.7), a real Review/confirm step satisfying error prevention for the financial transaction (3.3.4), and no auto-submit-on-input (3.2.2).\n\n### Perspectives With Findings \u2014 Grouped by ARRM Role\n\n**Front-End Dev**\n- Missing accessible name on `firstName` / `address` (label id mismatch) \u2014 Screen Reader \u2014 CRITICAL \u2014 3.3.2 / 4.1.2 (SR-1)\n- Inline errors not associated + error summary not announced \u2014 Screen Reader \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 3.3.1 / 4.1.3 (SR-2)\n- Step indicator exposes no current/completed state \u2014 Screen Reader \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 4.1.2 (SR-4)\n- Step transitions silent / unmanaged \u2014 Screen Reader \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 4.1.3 (SR-5)\n- No accessible name for voice control on `firstName` / `address` \u2014 Keyboard & Motor \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 2.5.3 (KM-1)\n- No `autocomplete` on personal/payment fields \u2014 Cognitive \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 1.3.5 (CN-1)\n- Error summary items are not links to fields \u2014 Screen Reader \u2014 MINOR \u2014 3.3.1/G139 (SR-3)\n\n**Visual Design**\n- Step-progress state conveyed by color alone (fails in CVD and forced-colors) \u2014 Environmental Contrast \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 1.4.1 (EC-1)\n- Default input border \u2248 1.6:1 (below 3:1) \u2014 Environmental Contrast \u2014 MAJOR \u2014 1.4.11 (EC-2)\n\n**UX Design**\n- (No primary-owned findings; appears as secondary on error-flow, step-transition, and step-indicator items above.)\n\n**Content Author**\n- (No primary-owned findings; secondary on label/scaffolding items.)\n\n### Open Questions Requiring Human Verification\n\n- `[Human verification required]` Does the integrated page wrap this form in a `<main>` landmark? (1.3.1 \u2014 SR-6)\n- `[Human verification required]` Does the page provide an `<h1>` above the component's `<h2>` headings? (2.4.6 \u2014 SR-6)\n- `[Human verification required]` Is `lang` set on the host `<html>` element? (3.1.1 \u2014 SR-6)\n- `[Human verification required]` Is a unique, per-step document `<title>` set for the SPA view? (2.4.2 \u2014 related to SR-5)\n\n### Recommended Next Step\n\n**BLOCK** \u2014 A CRITICAL finding is present (SR-1: two required inputs have no accessible name; fires the screen-reader red flag). Do not ship until SR-1 is resolved. The seven MAJOR findings \u2014 broken error association and silent validation (SR-2), unexposed step state and transitions (SR-4, SR-5), voice-control targeting (KM-1), color-only progress and low-contrast field borders (EC-1, EC-2), and missing autocomplete (CN-1) \u2014 must be addressed in the same fix pass before re-test. Re-run a11y-test (axe-core + keyboard walkthrough + a driven screen-reader session capturing live-region announcements) once fixes land, with particular attention to: field name resolution, `aria-describedby` error association, and announcement of both validation failures and step changes.\n",
